# Border Radius Rules

## Default: Medium (8px)

**ALWAYS use `rounded-md` (8px) as the default border radius** for all UI elements unless specifically instructed otherwise.

## The 4-Tier System

This design system uses only 4 border radius values:

| Name | Value | CSS Class | CSS Variable | When to Use |
|------|-------|-----------|--------------|-------------|
| Small | 4px | `rounded-sm` | `var(--radius-sm)` | ONLY when specifically requested for compact elements (checkboxes, small badges) |
| **Medium** | **8px** | **`rounded-md`** | **`var(--radius-md)`** | **DEFAULT - Use this for everything** |
| Large | 12px | `rounded-lg` | `var(--radius-lg)` | ONLY when specifically requested for large containers |
| Round | 9999px | `rounded-full` | `var(--radius-full)` | ONLY for circular elements (avatars, round buttons, pills) |

## Rules

### DO

1. **Use `rounded-md` by default** for:
   - Buttons
   - Input fields
   - Cards
   - Dropdown menus
   - Tooltips
   - Modal dialogs
   - Table containers
   - Any new component

2. **Only use other radii when explicitly specified**:
   - User says "small radius" or "compact" → use `rounded-sm`
   - User says "large radius" or "feature card" → use `rounded-lg`
   - User says "circular", "avatar", or "pill" → use `rounded-full`

### DON'T

1. **Never use arbitrary pixel values** like `border-radius: 10px` or `border-radius: 6px`
2. **Never mix different radii** on similar components

## CSS Variables

\`\`\`css
--radius-sm: 4px;     /* Small - only when requested */
--radius-md: 8px;     /* Medium - DEFAULT */
--radius-lg: 12px;    /* Large - only when requested */
--radius-full: 9999px; /* Round - for circles only */
--radius: 8px;        /* Alias - defaults to medium */
\`\`\`

## Examples

### Default (no specific instruction given)
\`\`\`tsx
// Using utility classes from utilities.css
<button className="rounded-md px-4 py-2">Click me</button>
<div className="rounded-md border p-4">Card content</div>
<input className="rounded-md border px-3 py-2" />

// Using inline styles with CSS variables
<button style={{ borderRadius: 'var(--radius-md)' }}>Click me</button>
\`\`\`

### When user asks for "small" or "compact"
\`\`\`tsx
// User specified small
<input type="checkbox" className="rounded-sm" />
<span className="rounded-sm px-1">Tag</span>
\`\`\`

### When user asks for circular elements
\`\`\`tsx
// Avatars and pills are circular
<img className="rounded-full" style={{ width: 40, height: 40 }} src="avatar.jpg" />
<span className="rounded-full px-3 py-1">Pill badge</span>
\`\`\`

## Available Utility Classes

The design system provides these border radius utility classes in \`utilities.css\`:

- \`.rounded-none\` - 0px
- \`.rounded-sm\` - 4px (var(--radius-sm))
- \`.rounded-md\` - 8px (var(--radius-md)) - DEFAULT
- \`.rounded-lg\` - 12px (var(--radius-lg))
- \`.rounded-full\` - 9999px (var(--radius-full))

Individual corner utilities are also available:
- \`.rounded-t-*\` - Top corners
- \`.rounded-r-*\` - Right corners
- \`.rounded-b-*\` - Bottom corners
- \`.rounded-l-*\` - Left corners
